value.value: Any cell that is part of the esophageal non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium. In humans, the esophagus, which requires flexibility to accommodate swallowing of a bolus, is covered with a non-keratinized epithelium.

A skeletal muscle fiber found in an embryo. In mammalian embryos, skeletal muscle expresses myosin heavy chain-embryonic (MyHC-emb, encoded by the MYH3 gene), which regulates skeletal muscle development.

label.value: fetal and neonatal skeletal muscle fiber

value.value: A skeletal muscle fiber found at the fetal and neonatal stages. In mammalian fetuses and neonates, skeletal muscle expresses myosin heavy chain-neonatal (MyHC-neo, encoded by the MYH8 gene). This expression disappears shortly after birth and is replaced by expression of adult heavy chain myosins.
A progenitor cell that is a tissue-resident mesenchymal cell, important for skeletal muscle regeneration, and able to differentiate into both adipocytes or fibroblasts.

A fibroblast located in the portal triad. Hepatic portal fibroblast are a non-parenchymal cell population located adjacent to bile duct epithelia in liver and are distinct from stellate cells. They differentiate into fibrogenic myofibroblasts during chronic injury states producing high levels of collagen.

definition.value: A reticular cell involved in directing B cells and T cells to specific regions within a tissue.

value.value: A specialized, fibroblastic reticular cell of mesenchymal origin found in lymph nodes. In human, it expresses several markers common to myofibroblasts (desmin, vimentin, CD73, CD90, α-smooth muscle actin (αSMA)), and can be differentiated from endothelial cells by its lack of CD31 expression. These cells are critical for the overall organization and function of the lymph node. Lymph node fibroblastic reticular cells (FRCs) can be further classified based on their location, function, and unique marker expression.
A fibroblastic reticular cell found in the lymph node subcapsular sinus.
A fibroblastic reticular cell found in the lymph node germinal center dark zone (B cell zone).

definition.value: B cell zone reticular cells share similarities with Ch25h-expresssing Ccl19lo T reticular cells found at the B cell follicle T zone interface of mouse lymph nodes.

value.value: A fibroblastic reticular cell found in the lymph node T cell domain.
A specialized fibroblast found in the medulla of lymph node.

definition.value: Origin and phenotype of medullary reticular cells are less well understood in humans than in mice.

label.value: lymphatic endothelial cell of subcapsular sinus ceiling

value.value: A lymphatic endothelial cell located in the subcapsular sinus ceiling of a lymph node. In human, it's characterized by a unique marker expression (NT5e+ and Caveolin-1+).

label.value: lymphatic endothelial cell of subcapsular sinus floor

value.value: A lymphatic endothelial cell located in the subcapsular sinus floor of a lymph node. In human, it's characterized by a unique marker expression (TNFRSF9+).
A lymphatic endothelial cell located in a lymph node trabecula.

label.value: lymphatic endothelial cell of medulla ceiling

value.value: A lymphatic endothelial cell located in the ceiling part of a lymph node medulla.
A germinal center B cell found in a lymph node germinal center light zone.
A germinal center B cell found in a lymph node germinal center dark zone.
A regulatory T cell present in the B cell follicles and germinal centers of lymphoid tissues. In humans, it is CXCR5+.

A B cell found in the perisinusoidal area of a lymph node. In humans, monocytoid B cells are a morphologically distinct B cell population
(oval nuclei, abundant cytoplasm, monocyte-like appearance), share many similarities with marginal zone B cells including marker expression, and are increased in disease settings.

label.value: lymph node lymphatic vessel endothelial cell

value.value: An endothelial cell located in a lymph node lymphatic vessel.

label.value: progenitor cell of mammary luminal epithelium

value.value: A progenitor cell with the potential to differentiate into luminal epithelial cells of mammary glands. In mouse, CD61 and c-kit were found to be coexpressed by the majority of, but not all, committed luminal progenitor cells.
A hair follicle matrix region cell which synthesizes keratin and undergoes a characteristic change as it moves upward from the hair bulb to become the hair medulla cortex and hair root sheath.

definition.value: A stromal cell that is part_of a bone marrow.
An epithelial cell that is part_of a umbilical artery.
A mononuclear cell that is part_of a bone marrow.

value.value: A specialized cardiomyocyte that transmit signals from the AV node to the cardiac Purkinje fibers.
Any blood vessel endothelial cell that is part of some heart.
Any cell that is part of some His-Purkinje system.
Any endothelial cell that is part of some heart.
Any photoreceptor cell that is part of some camera-type eye.
Any stellate neuron that has its soma located in some cerebellum.
A GABAergic interneuron whose soma is located in the cerebral cortex.
A CNS neuron of the cerebral cortex.
A highly specialized cell type exclusive to and forming neuroepithelium of the Saccus vasculosus, covering the caudal diverticulum of the infundibular recess.

definition.value: Editor note: remember to link to Saccus vasculosus in next uberon release

value.value: A cell with a flagellum surrounded by a collar of microvilli. The motion of the flagellum draws water past the microvilli, serving either a feeding or sensory function. Collar cells are found in multiple animals, including sponges, echinoderms, and cnidarians. They are also found outside animals in the choanoflagellates. Although collar cells are superficially similar, their cytoskeletal structure and functional biology are different in different groups of organisms.

definition.value: A zygote in a plant or an animal.

value.value: Any glial cell that is part of some heart.
Any myoblast that develops into some cardiac muscle cell.
A neuron that has its soma in the heart.

definition.value: This term is used in 3 GO terms that were created as part of the heart development focus project.

value.value: A CNS interneuron located in the dorsal horn of the spinal cord.
A motor neuron that passes from the spinal cord toward or to a muscle and conducts an impulse that causes movement.
A motor neuron that is generated only on limb levels and send axons into the limb mesenchyme.

definition.value: Need to MIREOT in 'spinal cord lateral column' from Uberon

value.value: A neurosecretory neuron residing mainly in the hypothalamic supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei and in a number of smaller accessory cell groups between these two nuclei, that is capable of secreting the hormones oxytocin or vasopressin, and sometimes both, into the systemic circulation.
A vetebrate lens cell that is any of the elongated, tightly packed cells that make up the bulk of the mature lens in a camera-type eye.
An interneuron that uses GABA as a vesicular neurotransmitter.  These interneurons are inhibitory

definition.value: The formal and textual definitions of this term will need to be altered if evidence for non-inhibitory GABA-ergic neurons emerges.

value.value: An inhibitory GABAergic interneuron found in the cerebellar cortex.
A cell in the area of mesoderm in the neurulating embryo that flanks and forms simultaneously with the neural tube. The cells of this region give rise to somites.
A hemocyte derived from the embryonic head mesoderm, which enters the hemolymph as a circulating cell.
